Calijah was excellent in Week 12, racking up two solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Caljah has been elite when healthy and can be counted as a DL2/DT1 regardless of opponent. Start him with confidence despite the tough om-paper matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Fiske was excellent in Week 12, racking up two solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Fiske has caught fire for the Rams and now has five of his six sacks in his last four contests (with three coming in the last two). Fiske has bullied his way into the DL2 conversation for Week 13 and should be treated as one despite the tough on-paper matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Sieler was excellent in Week 12, tallying three solos, one assist, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Sieler is up to four sacks on the season and has ridden his spike weeks to DL2 status in fppg. Still, it is safer to plug Sieler in as a DL3 as opposed to a DL2 on a non bye week. Treat him as such for Week 13 against the Green Bay Packers.

Latu impressed again in Week 12, racking up two solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Latu has just four sacks on the season but has now taken down the QB in two straight. Latu is a high-level talent and should be treated as a DL3/4, at least while he is cooking. Add and start Latu where needed as a DL3 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the New England Patriots.

A'Shawn was active in Week 12, racking up five solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Robinson has been a DL1 option since Week 6 and should be tapped as a top-25 play for Week 13 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Chop has caught fire for the Dolphins, most recently racking up two solos, two assists, 1.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Chop has just 3.5 sacks on the season, but all of them have come in his last four contests. Add Chop wherever possible as a DL3 with DL2 upside.

Williams was excellent in Week 12, tallying three solos, three assists, 2.5 sacks, three tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Williams is up to five sacks on the season but remains more DL3 than DL2 with no teams on bye. Act accordingly for Week 13 despite the plus matchup against the New York Jets.

Clowney showed up in Week 12, tallying two solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss. Clowney is still a plus run defender but has just 2.5 sacks on the season and is far from the everydown impact player he was just last season in Baltimore. Clowney is nothing more than a desperation flex2 in 11 v 11 leagues. Leave him on benches or the waiver wire for Week 13.

Tyree was at it again in Week 12, notching three solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Tyree has just three sacks on the season, but all three have come in his last four contests. Wilson has recorded a sack in back-to-back games and in three of his last four and is finally living up to his potential across from Maxx Crosby. Add Tyree as a DL3/4 for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Kansas City Cg=hiefs,

Milton Williams continues to impress for the Eagles, most recently notching two solos, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one fumble recovery. Milton is up to five sacks on the season and is thriving in the odd front alongside Jalen Carter and Jordan Davis.

Kinlaw showed up in Week 11, racking up two solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Kinlaw has just 2.5 sacks on the season and has yet to make good on his raw tools at any point in his career. Still, he is a worthy DT3 option but should be far from minds as a DL3 or even a DL4 option. Look elsewhere for your Week 13 DT2/DL3.

Barnett is heating up for the Houston Texans, most recently tallying three solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Barnett now has a sack in two straight, making him worthy of roster consideration. The truly desperate can chase the sacks, but in a non bye week, you shouldnt find yourself in that deep of a bind unless you play in a 20+ team league. Add Barnett where needed but keep him glued to benches until his role expands (not happening with Will Anderson and Danielle Hunter healthy) or he becomes undeniable. Look elsewhere for your Week 13 DL4/flex2.

Zaire did Zaire things in Week 12, tallying eight solos, five assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The LB6 on the season, Zaire can be counted as a top-five option regardless of opponent. Treat him as such for a plus Week 13 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Speed was solid in Week 12, reeling off six solos and five assists. The LB3 in fppg, Speed should be counted as a top-five option regardless of opponent. Tap him as an LB1 for a plus Week 13 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Wagner was excellent in Week 12, racking up five solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. The LB15 on the season, Wagner can be counted as a top-10 option week in and week out. Fire him up with confidence for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Kendricks was excellent in Week 12, racking up four solos, six assists, and one fumble recovery. The LB9 on the season, fire Kendricks up as a top-10 option for Turkey Day Football against the New York Giants.

Luvu was excellent in Week 12, racking up five solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and three passes defended. The LB12 on the season, Luvu should be treated as a top-15 option for a drool-worthy Week 13 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Nakobe was excellent in Week 12, racking up five solos, three assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one fumble recovery. Nakobe had exceeded all expectations, powering his way to the LB5 through 12 weeks of action. Nakobe looks like he will be locked in as an LB1 for years to come. Fire him up as a top-12 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Brooks was excellent in Week 12, racking up seven solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, and one fumble recovery. Brooks has caught fire in recent weeks and is an easy top-15 play for Week 13 despite a tough on-paper matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Foye was solid in Week 11, racking up six solos and three assists. Foye is back into the swing of things and is safe to trust as a top-10 option again. Fire him up with confidence for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Azeez was excellent in Week 12, racking up five solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The LB14 on the season, Azeez should be treated as a top-12 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars.

Quay was excellent in Week 12, tallying six solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Quay has been an elite IDP option this season and comes into Week 13 as the LB22. Treat him as a top-15 option for Week 13, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Okereke was excellent in Week 12, tallying five solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. Okereke has been solid this season but hasn't lived up to the LB1 status some expected of him. His spike weeks keep him in the LB2 conversation, and he can be counted as one for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Bernard was excellent in Week 11, racking up three solos, five assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Bernard hasn't quite been the LB1 many were hoping for on draft day but has still provided solid LB2 production. Treat him as a top-20 option for Sunday Night Football against the San Francisco 49ers.

Overshown flashed in Week 12, tallying one solo, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. DeMarvion has been a strong LB2 option and should be counted as a top-25 option for Week 13 against the New York Giants.

Murray was at it again in Week 12, racking up six solos, one assist, two tackles for loss, one interception, and two passes defended. Murray has caught fire over the last two weeks and is an easy LB2 play going forward. Treat him as such for Week 13 despite no teams being on bye. Start him with confidence as a top-25 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against Washington.

Jewell was excellent in Week 12, tallying six solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Jewell has had multiple spike weeks and has been a strong LB2 option when he has been on the field. Treat him as a top-25 option for Week 13 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. Add Jewell wherever possible.

Kaden Elliss was excellent in Week 11, notching eight solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. The LB15 on the season, Elliss continues to impress for the Falcons and can confidently be counted as an LB2 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Barton was excellent in Week 12, racking up five solos, one assist, 0.5 sacks, and one pass defended. Barton is a boom-or-bust play but has strung together two strong weeks in a row ahead of a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns. Add and start Barton where needed.

Knight continues to impress for the Seahawks, most recently notching five solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Knight has proven why the Seahawks were comfortable releasing Tyrel Dodson with his strong play, and looks like a solid complement for Ernest Jones. Knight is a strong LB3 play for Week 13 and beyond and should be added and started in all competitive leagues.

Rozeboom was excellent in Week 12, tallying seven solos, five assists, and one tackle for loss. Rozeboom has put together spike weeks in three of his last four games and should be treated as an LB2 option for Week 13, thanks to a plus matchup against the New Orleans Saints. Start Rozeboom where needed.

McFadden was excellent in Week 12, racking up six solos and five assists. McFadden has been inconsistent in the solo department but has posted enough spike weeks to remain in the LB2 conversation during the byes. Treat McFadden as an Lb3 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Hicks was excellent in Week 12, tallying two solos, four assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Hicks is an LB3/4 option who will have spike weeks thanks to his disruptive presence in both the run and the pass games. Add Hicks as a depth option where needed ahead of a plus Week 14 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Parsons showed up in a big way in Week 12, reeling off four solos, four assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. He is up to five sacks, with four coming in his last three games. Parsons has two sacks in two of his last three games and is back in the DL1 mix despite the bagel they sandwiched. Fire Parsons up as a top-12 option for a tasty Week 13 matchup against the New York Giants.

Demario was excellent in Week 11, tallying three solos, 10 assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Demario has slipped into flex territory this season but is worth a look as an LB3 option if you find yourself in a pinch. He remains an LB4/flex for Week 13 but will be in the LB3 conversation for Week 14, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Giants.

AVG was excellent in Week 12, notching three solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended against the Chicago Bears. The DL1 on the season, AVG has nine sacks, two picks, and two touchdowns. Treat him as a top-10 option for Week 13 despite the neutral-at-best matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Malik was excellent on Monday night, tallying seven solos, six assists, and one tackle for loss. Harrison shined with Roquan Smith sidelined and may finally be ready to realize his potential after building some confidence against the Chargers. Treat Malik as an LB3 option for Week 13, thanks to the plus matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Herbig showed up in Week 12, notching three solos, two assists, one sack, and one forced fumble. Herbig has flashed but does not have a consistent enough role to trust, especially in a non bye week. Look elsewhere for your Week 13 DL4.

Cross was at it again in Week 12, tallying six solos, eight assists, and two tackles for loss. Cross has been elite all season and is currently the DB3 in fppg. Treat him as a top-five option for Week 13 despite the neutral at best matchup against the New England Patriots.

Budda was excellent again in Week 12, racking up four solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. The DB1 on the season, Baker is a top-five IDP option regardless of position, thanks to his consistency. Start him as a top-three DB option despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Minnesota Vikings.

Winfield was at it again in Week 12, tallying three solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. The DB6/S4 on the season, Winfield is an easy top-five option regardless of opponent.

Byard was excellent in Week 12, racking up 11 solos and two assists. Byard has been on fire since Week 9, helping vault him up to the DB8 in fppg on the season. Fire Byard up as a top-15 option despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Detroit Lions.

McKinney was excellent in Week 13, notching three solos, one interception, and two passes defended. Xavier is up to seven interceptions, which has helped push him to the DB14 on the season. He will have his down weeks, but his upside is too significant to ignore. Treat McKinney as a DB2 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Jones was excellent in Week 12, reeling off five solos, one interception, and two passes defended. Jones has produced multiple splash weeks en route to DB9 status in fppg and should be treated as a DB1 option the rest of the way. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Delpit showed up in Week 12, notching six solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Delpit has recorded five or more solos in four of his last five games, making him one of the more consistent options at the position. This was his first true spike week since Week 3, making him more DB3 than DB2 despite the strong solo numbers. Add and start Delpit where needed as a DB3 option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Nubin went off in Week 12, tallying five solos, seven assists, and one pass defended. The rookie has been inconsistent but has now stacked back-to-back DB1-level outings together, highlighting his upside. He is a top-25 option for Week 13 but has a lower floor than most. Fire him up with confidence for the plus matchup against the Dallas Cowboys. Add and start Nubin where possible.

DeShon was excellent in Week 12, racking up four solos, two assists, one forced fumble, one fumble recovery, and one pass defended. The DB9/S7 on the season, DeShon is safe to count on as a top-10 option regardless of opponent. Treat him as such for Week 13 against Cincinnati.

Bates was excellent in Week 11, racking up five solos, five assists, one pass defended, and one forced fumble. Bates is the DB6 overall and the DB14 in fppg. Treat him as a top-12 option for Week 13 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.

Woods was excellent in Week 12, racking up seven solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Woods has started to heat back up for the Panthers and should be counted as a DB2 option now that he is back into the swing of things. Add and start Woods wherever possible.

Smith was excellent in Week 12, tallying nine solos and two assists. Smith is starting to heat up for the Vikings and is back in the DB2 conversation for Week 13 despite the tough on-paper matchup against the Arizona Cardinals. Add Harrison wherever possible.

Poyer showed up in Week 12, tallying seven solos and one pass defended. Poyer has been incredibly inconsistent in Miami and remains more DB4 than DB3 for Week 13. Treat him as such for the plus matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Rapp showed up in Week 11, tallying three solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Rapp has quietly strung together three strong weeks in a row and should be treated as a DB2/3 option for Week 13 despite no teams being on bye, thanks to a plus matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

CJGJ was solid in Week 12, tallying four solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Gardner-Johnson hasn't quite lived up to the expectations many placed on him in his return to Philadelphia but is still a serviceable DB3 who offers DB1-level upside. Treat him as a top-36 option for Week 13 despite the neutral at best Week 13 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Owens was excellent in Week 12, racking up four solos, four assists, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Owens has been sparingly used on offense and only got the starting nod due to Elijah Hicks being injured. Leave him on benches unless Hicks is ruled out.

Ward went bonkers in Week 12, exploding for six solos, three tackles for loss, one interception, one pass defended, and one touchdown. Ward has had two spike weeks in his three games since returning from injury and should be treated as an easy DB3 option for Week 13 despite the neutral at best on paper matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars. Add Ward wherever needed.

Izien was solid in Week 12, notching five solos and five assists. Izien has had some splash weeks, but extremely low production in his down weeks have kept him out of the DB2 conversation. Treat him as a low-end DB3 for a tough on-paper matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

DTD was excellent in Week 12, tallying six solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He has been solid in relief of the injured Jalen Thompson and is worth a look as a DB3 if he gets another start on Sunday, as expected. DTD has recorded five or more solos in both of his spot starts and is a top-36 option for Week 13 despite the tough on-paper matchup.

Geno Stone was excellent in Week 11, tallying eight solos, one assist, and one fumble recovery. Stone hasn't quite lived up to expectations after coming over from the division rival Baltimore Ravens, as Stone, as a backup and injury replacement, was second in the NFL with seven interceptions. Stone makes for a solid depth option but will need to be stashed through the bye. Tap Stone as a DB3/4/flex option for a plus Week 13 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.
